{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"31922432-faee-4715-b79e-c96c59f626c7","content":"The project directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users run (e.g. `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType` | Must be `Exe` for tools |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server\n```\n\nThat's it — `PackAsTool` + `ToolCommandName` are the two essential properties that turn a console app into an installable dotnet tool.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"001bbc95-7656-4ba0-a517-22eacde90ab3","outputTokens":469,"requestId":"8438:291A22:FBF05F:13D098A:69FFDB46"},"id":"3fc6cf28-d09e-4197-b9dc-804421ce6e62","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:11:43.086Z","parentId":"e6da5e81-b0fc-43cb-8504-bb03c2e307e2"}
